acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Winemaker André Tchelistcheff (1901-1994), known as "the dean of wine" and "the Maestro", studied agriculture in Czechoslovakia at the University of Brno and later studied viticulture and enology at the Pasteur Institute and the Institut National Agronomique in Paris. He came to California in 1938 at the invitation of Georges de Latour, owner of Beaulieu Vineyard, who was seeking a winemaker who could bring European methods to his winery. During his time at Beaulieu, Tchelistcheff introduced the now standard practices of fermenting white wines in a cold room and using malolactic fermentation as an essential part of making red wines. Tchelistcheff remained at Beaulieu until his retirement in 1973, after which he worked as a consulting enologist for many winemakers and wineries, including Robert Mondavi, Louis M. Martini, Franciscan Vineyards, Firestone, Jordan, and Buena Vista in California, and Chateau Ste. Michelle in Washington. Following retirement, Tchelistcheff also conducted a series of tours for winemakers through Wine Tours International, the first of which coincided with the famous 1976 Paris Tasting. In 1991, Tchelistcheff returned to Beaulieu as a consultant and worked there until his death in 1994.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Scrapbooks, photograph albums, clippings, awards, memorabilia, and papers curated by Dorothy Tchelistcheff, wife of André Tchelistcheff. The collection documents winemaker André Tchelistcheff's life and work from 1967-1994, especially his work with Beaulieu Vineyards, and memorial events in his honor from 1994 to 2001.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Until it closed its doors in 1994, the <cite>Sacramento Union</cite> was the oldest daily newspaper west of the Mississippi.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip:
The archives contain 660 bound volumes and some accounting and business records from the early years of the newspaper. The photograph files run daily from 1966 to 1994. The clipping files provide subject access for 1972 through 1992. And the business records cover the last eighteen months of the newspaper's struggle to survive. The collection provides a wealth of information for researchers interested in the Sacramento region in the last quarter of the 20th century.
  • Microfilm format
The use copy of the Sacramento Union is the microfilm which is available for 1851-1994. Shields Library holds the microfilm for the years 1851-1854; 1856-1864 and 1869-1994. Researchers are welcome to use the microfilm, located in the lower level of Shields Library, anytime Shields Library is open. Other local repositories that hold the Sacramento Union microfilm include the California State University, Sacramento Library, Sacramento Public Library, and the California State Library. Researchers not in the Davis area should contact their local public library to explore options to borrow the microfilm via inter-library loan.
  • Digital format
The California Newspaper Project has digitized the Sacramento Daily Union for 1851-1899 and the Sacramento Union for 1906-1922. Search for articles on their website. The Library of Congress Chronicling America Collection has digitized the Sacramento Daily Record-Union for 1880-1891 and the Record-Union for 1891-1899.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Botany, University of California, Davis.

Videotape and transcript of Walters' speech, "Unsung heroines of Yolo County" (1992), and a bibliography of Yolo County histories.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Computer Science, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Reports dealing with campus and system-wide computer issues, research on computers, correspondence, drafts, manuals, maps.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The club was founded to foster and support cultural activities in the Davis community.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: By-laws, meeting minutes, and list of discussion group members.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Agricultural Engineering, University of California, Davis (1928-1951); author of <cite>Research in Mechanical Farm Equipment</cite> (1928); instrumental figure in the development of the sugar beet harvester.

Correspondence from contemporary poets regarding reading arrangements in the California area.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Design, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Books, serial publications, artwork.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Agricultural Economics, University of California (1925-1958); Dean of Students and Vice-Chair of the Statewide Department of Agricultural Economics (1952-1957).

Clippings pertaining to the cultivation of fruits, including grapes and nuts, ornamental plants, forest trees, and garden vegetables, as well as gadgets and tools used for their maintenance.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Water Science, University of California, Davis (1918-1954).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Clippings, correspondence, financial papers, legal documents, and programs pertaining to London's Vauxhall Gardens. Accounts and salary details, legal and insurance fees, and auction records.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Native American Studies, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Articles by Varese, correspondence, and lecture and conference materials.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Director, Agriculture Section, California Chamber of Commerce.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Music, University of California, Davis (1972-1993).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Comparative Literature, University of California, Davis.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Scientific director of the Armed Forces Institute (1959-1967) and founding Chair of the Department of Pathology at the University of California, Davis School of Medicine.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Biographical materials, Stowell's writings and correspondence, as wellas his slide collection which documents his travels around the world.Also included are files related to organizations that he was affiliatedwith including: Universities Associated for Research and Education inPathology (UAREP), Armed Forces Institute of Pathology (AFIP) andAmerican Registry of Pathology (ARP).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Soils and Plant Nutrition, University of California, Davis, with a research focus on plant chemistry and energy resources.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Subject files relating to soil science, plant chemistry, fertilizers, and genetics; correspondence, reports, contracts, clippings, photographs, and reprints; personal files.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Ph.D., University of California, Berkeley (1921); Curator of Birds, Museum of Vertebrate Zoology, University of California, Berkeley (1914-1923); Professor of Zoology, University of California, Davis (1923-1956); co-author of <cite>Animal life in the Yosemite</cite> (1926) and <cite>Natural history of the Sierra Nevada</cite> (1968).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Original, revised and intermediate proofs for <cite>Elements of zoology</cite> (1955), and correspondence related to both research and travel. Also included are photographs and postcards of the California missions.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Botanical artist who served for twenty-five years as the principal illustrator for <cite>Curtis's Botanical Magazine</cite> and worked under commission for the Royal Botanical Gardens, Kew, England.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Six original watercolors of Northern California plants, painted in 1987 while Stones was visiting California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Instructor, Agricultural Engineering Department, University of California (1921-1929), Agricultural Engineering Consultant, U.S.S.R Grain Trust (1930-1931), various positions at Caterpillar Tractor Company (1932-1958)
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material regarding mechanized farming in U.S.S.R.; photographs.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Charles L. Stilson (1844-1922) was a businessman in Chico,California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains twenty-three letters, the majority of which are written to Stilson by the aunt who raised him, Elizabeth L. Stilson. The letters discuss life in Chico, family news, and Stilson's business dealings.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Parasitology and Entomologist in the Experiment Station, University of California, Berkeley.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material about the Oriental fruit moth and other entomological concerns.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: John Innes Mackintosh Stewart (1906-1994) was a Scottish writer and academic. He taught English at the University of Leeds; the University of Adelaide, South Australia; Queen's University, Belfast; and Oxford University. Stewart wrote both literary criticism and novels under his own name and mystery novels under the name Michael Innes.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence with J.I.M. Stewart, receipts for books, dust jackets, and manuscripts of novels and short stories.
Material regarding world military history (20th century), especially Vietnam; government publications, reprints.
Two handwritten essays, one fragment, "The weather and our food prospects," and "The duration of life and average amount of sickness of the tarious trades."

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Service maintenance man for Best Tractor Company and a dealer for Case.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Contains an article entitled "An Old (Case) Tractor Story," published in <cite>Old Abe's News</cite> (1988) and an unpublished manuscript entitled "The Cat Crawled Into the Woods and Ran...", recalling Steiner's experiences at Best Tractor Company during the 1920's, when he was occasionally sent to work in logging camps in Oregon or Northern California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Ph.D., Harvard University; Professor of Genetics, University of California, Davis (1950-1973); Member, National Academy of Sciences; author of <cite>Darwin to DNA: molecules to humanity</cite> (1982) and <cite>The human organism and the world of life</cite> (1983).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Research papers, correspondence, class materials and lecture notes.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Entomology, University of California, Davis (1958-1973).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence with chemical companies, farmers, and researchers regarding agricultural pests and their control.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Squat Theatre began in 1969 as the Kassak Studio in Budapest, Hungary. Pressured by the Hungarian government because of its political and aesthetic radicalism, the group left Hungary in 1976. Calling itself Elephant Theatre, the troupe performed in western Europe for one year. Then, adopting the name Squat Theatre they emigrated to the U.S. Squat received an Obie Award in 1978 for its original piece entitled <cite>Pig, Child, Fire</cite> and has since established itself as an important part of New York's avant-garde theatre.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Audio-visual materials, correspondence, ephemera, financial records, legal documents, photographs, programs, promotional materials, and scripts, providing an extensive historical record of the expatriate Hungarian theatre troupe from the time of its inception in Budapest in 1969 to its activities in the avant-garde theatre scene in New York City during the 1980's.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: <cite>Squaring the Circle</cite>, a play written by Russian dramatist Valentin Katayev, was first produced at the Moscow Art Theatre in 1928. TheUnited States production, translated by Charles Malamuth and Eugene Lyons, premiered at the Pasadena Community Playhouse in August 1935 and was later performed at the Broad Street Theatre in Philadelphia and at the Lyceum and Adelphi Theatres in New York City.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, photographs, and ephemera relating to the play's 1935U.S. production. Also included are several images of the cast that performed at the Moscow Art Theatre.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: In 1881, businessman Claus Spreckels (1828-1908) founded Spreckels SugarCompany in California's San Joaquin Valley.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Annual reports of the Spreckels Sugar Company's experiment station (1909-1912); company agricultural reports (1919); United States SugarManufacturers' Association leaflets and reports (1916-1931); USDA reports on the beet-sugar industry (1897); and one twentieth-century pamphlet on the beet sugar industry.

title.rendered: Spieker, Warren E., Jr. Collection of Oral Histories of Waterfowl Hunters

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Forty-three audiotapes of oral histories of California waterfowl hunters. Transcriptions of the interviews are included.

title.rendered: Spicer, James and Morris Ploscowe. Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: James Spicer was the Living Theatre's General Manager from 1959 to 1963 and from 1970 to 1974. Morris Ploscowe was the Living Theatre's attorney for several years.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, ephemera, legal documents, programs, and promotional materials. Among the most significant items in this collection are Ploscowe's files regarding the political activities of Julian Beck and Judith Malina, co-founders of the Living Theatre, and Judith Malina's diaries.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Howard O. Spencer (1838-1918) served as a Mormon missionary in England and was an early settler of the town of Orderville, Utah.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Eighteen letters, the majority of which are written by Spencer to his family while he was serving as a missionary in England. Also included is one letter written to Spencer by Brigham Young Jr. while Young was in England. The letters discuss Spencer's life in England, family news, and religion.

title.rendered: Special Libraries Association. Sierra Nevada Chapter. Records.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Special Libraries Association (SLA) is an international professional association of members who work in special libraries serving business, research, medicine, government, universities, media, museums and institutions that use or produce specialized information. The Sierra Nevada Chapter membership is comprised primarily of individuals residing or working in Northern California and Nevada.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Slides, memoranda, diskettes, budgets, flyers of dinner events, executive board meeting minutes and v.1-26 of the <cite>Gold & Silver Gazette</cite>, the Sierra Nevada Chapter's newsletter.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Teacher, and artist for Latino and other minority youth in the Sacramento area.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Artwork, sketchbooks, proof sets, manuscripts, papers.
Texts of presentations given to the Society of Automotive Engineers and the American Society of Agricultural Engineers discussing a wide variety of topics related to agricultural technology.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Historian at Yosemite National Park, author of <cite>Wilderness historic resources survey</cite> (1988-1989) for the Yosemite Valley.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Serials, pamphlets, and articles relating to Native Americans and the literature of the American west.

title.rendered: Snyder, Gary. Letters to Cid Corman.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Gary Snyder (1930- ), poet, essayist, translator, Zen Buddhist, environmentalist, lecturer, and teacher, is considered one of the most significant environmental writers of the twentieth century.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Letters from Gary Snyder in Japan to Cid Corman in the United States.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Poet, essayist, translator, Zen Buddhist, environmentalist, and teacher, Gary Snyder is considered one of the most significant environmental writers of the twentieth century and a central figure in environmental activism.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The Gary Snyder Papers contain his manuscripts and published works, correspondence, recordings, and subject files. Manuscripts and publications by other authors, serials, ephemera, and memorabilia are also found in the collection.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Blog post about the collection

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis (1964-1990), with a research focus on the history of American education. Author of <cite>Professors and Public Ethics</cite> (1956) and <cite>Cities of Our Past and Present</cite> (1964).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Typescript used in the publication of <cite>Theories of Education in Early America, 1655-1819</cite> (1973) edited by Smith, lecture notes, correspondence.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Actor and stage manager who first appeared in the United States at the Walnut Street Theatre in Philadelphia in 1827. During his later years he was both actor and stage manager at the California Theatre in San Francisco.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Five holograph sides, presumably for roles Smith performed at theCalifornia Theatre in San Francisco. Sides are defined as pagescontaining an actor's part and cue words.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Historian, collector. Great grandson of William B. Waddell, member of freighting firm of Russell, Majors and Waddell, founders of Pony Express (1860). Smith retired from military service (1949) to devote time to study and promotion of Pony Express history. He settled in San Rafael, Calif. and organized a Pony Express History and Art Gallery.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Social and business correspondence of Waddell Smith, financial records of Smith's Pony Express Museum, photographs, newspaper clippings, Pony Express memorabilia, and Overland Mail Centennial Association records.
Material regarding women's services for "Displaced Homemakers."

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Michael Peter Smith served as Professor of Community Studies andDevelopment at the University of California, Davis from 1986-2010.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains his writings as well as research materialsrelated to his books: Citizenship Across Borders: The PoliticalTransnationalism of El Migrante (2008) and Transnational Urbanism:Locating Globalization (2001).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Extension Entomologist, Agricultural Experiment Station (1943-1963); Professor of Entomology, University of California, Davis (1943-1963).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence to researchers and growers regarding the control of crop pests.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Designer, developer, and general contractor, Smith designed and built the 300-acre Stonegate planned development in Davis, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Materials related to Smith's Stonegate development in Davis, California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: 1917 graduate of the University Farm School (now the University of California, Davis) who served with the United States Army Medical Corps in France during the First World War. An outstanding athlete, Slater won Olympic gold medals for rugby in 1920 and 1924. Around 1927, he bought land in Clarksburg, California where he farmed for many years.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, diaries, publications, ephemera, photographic material, and realia. Most of the collection pertains to Slater and the United States Olympic Rugby Team winning gold medals at the Olympic Games in Antwerp, Belgium (1920) and Paris (1924). The collection also includes material related to the history of the University of California, Davis; the First World War; agriculture; and the history of Yolo County, California
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Website highlighting the Colby E. "Babe" Slater Collection and the return of rugby to the Olympics

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Al Logan Slagle was a member of the United Keetoowah Band of the Cherokee of Oklahoma and worked as an attorney for the Association of American Indian Affairs (AAIA) in Washington, D.C. Prior to that he worked for the California Indian Legal Services in Oakland. He was the co-author of the book, <cite>The Good Red Road</cite> (1987). He completed his doctorate at Loyola University and was admitted to the California State Bar in 1979 then beginning his career in defending the rights of Native American tribes. His research included making use of National Archives Indian rolls, family genealogies, tribal records, and other documents to write petitions for Native American tribes seeking official legal tribal status.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection includes his research files and petitions on behalf of a number of tribes.
Leaves from the Tyndale, Redman, Hollybushe, and Regvault bibles, mostly original, some annotated, as well as assorted unidentified leaves.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Viticulture and Enology, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, class materials, research files, wine judging files, published writings and patents, various committee files, speeches, and biobibliographies.
Photographs of Native Americans, Bear Dance, and petroglyphs.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Spanish Literature, University of California, Santa Cruz; co-editor of <cite>Judeo-Spanish ballads from New York</cite> (1981) and <cite>Hispania Judaica</cite> (1980-1984).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Pamphlets, reprints, photocopies, and other material relating to the history of Spanish literature, with particular emphasis on the picaresque novel.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Ph.D (Dramatic Art) University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material regarding Shragge's exhibit titled "Soviet Jewish Theatre Design".

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Peter J. Shields presided as a Superior Court Judge in Sacramento County from 1900 to 1949. In 1905, Shields wrote the legislation that led to the establishment of the University Farm. He maintained his association with the campus until his death in 1962.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The Peter J. Shields Collection contains both personal papers and materials related to the creation of the University of California, Davis campus.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis; compiler of <cite>A preliminary list of references for the history of agriculture in California</cite> (1967); editor of <cite>Agriculture in the development of the far west</cite> (1975).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Reprints and serial titles relating to California agricultural history.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Copies of patents, articles, bibliographies, photographs, manuscripts, and research notes relating to patents and inventions, with a particular emphasis on the role of the U.S. Bureau of the Budget in science and technology policy decisions.

Music & lyrics for songs from films, musicals, and theatre.The sheet music in this collection has been cataloged individually in the Harvest Library catalog. To find the sheet music, search in Harvest author = Sheet Music Collection. A quick link to that search is provided below as "Search Harvest Catalog."

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Art, University of California, Davis (1959-1982).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence and notes; sketchbooks; prints; photographsof his work; personal photographs; teaching materials; and exhibit filesand announcements.
Typescript biography of Theodore Benjamin Shank, with an emphasis on his years of farming in the Imperial Valley, California in the early part of the 20th century.

title.rendered: Shaffer, Jack. Collection of Cooperatives Materials.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Coordinator of Cooperative Development for the United States Agency for International Development; Executive Director of the Committee for the Promotion and Advancement of Cooperatives; and author of the <cite>Historical Dictionary of the Cooperative Movement</cite> (1999).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Books and serials relating to a wide range of domestic and international cooperatives ranging from agrarian to financial to healthcare cooperatives, among others.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Niles Searls (1825-1907) served as State Senator and Chief Justice of the California Supreme Court.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Several letters to Niles Searls and his son Fred Searls, as well as materials related to Fred Searls' involvement with the Zeibright Mine in Nevada City, California.
Artists books created by Scott throughout her lifetime.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material regarding Schwab's work about <cite>Diderot's Encyclopedie</cite>.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Ellen Isham Schutt (1873-1955) was an illustrator with the United States Department of Agriculture who was active from 1904-1914.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: 286 original watercolors of fruits, mostly apples, rendered by Schutt for the University of California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Digitized images from this collection are available on Calisphere

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Once involved in World War II German reeducation camps.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, speeches, typescripts of novels, book reviews, and short stories, mostly in German.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Illustrator/science fiction artist
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Artwork and correspondence. The group of science fiction illustrations includes roughly 500 drawings, sketches and photomechanical reproductions as well as photographs used as reference for sketches as well as a small collection of correspondence from such science fiction authors as Isaac Asimov.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Blog post about the collection

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Nutrition at the University of California, Davis(1976-2007). Schneeman also served as Chair of the Department ofNutrition (1988-1993), Dean of the College of Agricultural andEnvironmental Sciences (1993-1999), and Associate Vice Provost forUniversity Research (2001-2004).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Materials related to Schneeman's teaching at UC Davis inthe Department of Nutrition; her service as Chair of the Department ofNutrition and of Dean of the College of Agricultural and EnvironmentalSciences; and her work as Assistant Administrator for Nutrition in theAgricultural Research Service of the U.S. Department of Agriculture(USDA). The collection also includes a small set of photographs.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Director of the California National Primate Research Center (1963-1968).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Early photographs, 35mm and lantern slides of the California National Primate Research Center.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Theodore G. Schmeiser was President of Schmeiser Manufacturing Company, which produced almond hullers in the early 1900s. He was credited with bringing the first water supply system to Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Collection includes articles, brochures, photographs, and handouts.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Writer and editor with an emphasis on agriculture and University of California topics. Author of <cite>Abundant harvest: the history of the University of California, Davis</cite>.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs relating to California agriculture, some of which were used in the Guidebook; reports, clippings, and notes relating to the early College of Agriculture and the University Farm at Davis.
Assorted service grams, bulletins, product brochures for Caterpillar & Deere.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: California poet
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscripts, poems, correspondence, photographs.
Correspondence and publications about brandy and cognac.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Farm reporter columnist for the <cite>San Francisco Chronicle</cite> (1959-1994); farm radio broadcaster; Vice president and corporate secretary of California Canners and Growers; Director of Information, Division of Agricultural Sciences, University of California; chairman, Advisory Council of the University of California, Division of Agricultural Sciences; president, U.S. National Fruit Export Council.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Clippings, correspondence, manuscripts, periodicals, and promotional materials relating Schacht's work as a farm reporter with the <cite>San Francisco Chronicle</cite> and the National Broadcasting Company as well as his public relations activities for the California Canners and Growers organization.

title.rendered: Scenes of England and Wales Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Twenty matted prints depicting various topographical scenes in England and Wales.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Founded in 1918, the League is leader of the movement to preserve the coast redwood and giant sequoia.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Typecript of memo about the League's land acquisition and money sources.
Business correspondence about the building of Satterlee's house in Atlantic Highlands, New Jersey.

Collection of periodicals that focus on bicycles and cycling. Titles include: <cite>Velo-News</cite>, <cite>Winning</cite>, <cite>Berkeley Bike Club Newsletter/Pneusletter</cite>, <cite>Cycle</cite>, <cite>Cycling USA</cite>, <cite>NCNCA (Northern California/Nevada Cycling Association) Newsletter</cite>, and <cite>NORBA News: official publication of the National Off-Road Bicycle Association</cite>.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Dramatic Art, University of California, Davis (1963-1993).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Books, clippings, correspondence, drawings, manuscripts, microforms, photographs, programs, published material, realia, serials, scripts, and research material resulting in Sarlos' <cite>Jig Cook and the Provincetown players</cite> (1982); also includes items documenting Sarlos' attempt to reconstruct the Luzern Passion Play; notes and research materials relating to the Department of Dramatic Art, University of California, Davis.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Saratoga Horticultural Research Foundation was formed in 1952 by California horticulturalists and gardeners whose goal was to improve and introduce new species of shade and ornamental trees and native western shrubs to our local landscapes. In 2006-2007, the SHRF disbanded, after successfully accomplishing many of their goals, along with the help of nurseries and the landscape industry.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The records of the organization as well as plant propagation and description records, nursery records, plant photographs and slides, andplan evaluations.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Online exhibit about the collection
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo2_name: View digitized film from the collection on the Internet Archive

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Northern California storyteller and poet; author of <cite>The confounding: a Paiute tale to be told aloud</cite> (1980); <cite>The adventures of High John the Conqueror</cite> (1989); and <cite>American Zen: by a guy who tried it</cite> (1994).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Personal journals, manuscripts, correspondence, publications, audio tapes, and collected ephemera relating to Sanfield's life and career.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Blog post about the collection

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Founded by Ronald G. Davis in 1959 and later reorganized as a collective, the San Francisco Mime Troupe is one of the oldest continuing radical theatre groups in the United States.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Audio-visual materials, business records, correspondence, designs, ephemera, films, financial records, legal documents, photographs, promotional materials, and scripts; extensive documentation of the Troupe's activities during the 1960's and 1970's.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Blog post about the collection

title.rendered: San Francisco Ballad Slips and Song Sheets Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Fourteen ballad slips and song sheets that comment on the social and political climate of the post-Civil War era.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Asian American Studies, University of California, Davis (1999-2002).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscripts, correspondence, photographic materials, clippings, audiotapes, and memorabilia relating to San Buenaventura’s research on Filipino American history. Also included is material on Hilario Moncado and the Filipino Federation of America.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Nanao Sakaki (1923-2008), Japanese poet, authored <cite>Break the Mirror</cite>, <cite>Let's Eat Stars</cite>, and <cite>Real Play</cite>, among other works. He was a leading figure in the Tribe, a Japanese sub-culture group.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscripts and published works by Sakaki, articles about and interviews with Sakaki, videocassettes of his readings, photographs, and ephemera.
Bidding instructions for Upper American River Transmission Lines Project.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Founded in 1939 by a secondhand book dealer, a schoolteacher, and a newspaperman, the Sacramento Book Collectors Club's purpose is to create finely printed editions of unique works describing Sacramento history.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Typescript and proofs for the translated journals of the Duke of Wurttemberg (Friedrich Paul Wilhelm), a new world explorer and naturalist whose travels took him to Sacramento in 1851-1852. The translation was printed in an edition of 400 copies by the Grabhorn Hoyem Press and published by the Sacramento Book Collectors Club in 1973.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: M.S., Horticulture, University of California, Berkeley (1923); Agricultural Extension Agent specializing in subtropical horticulture, at University of California, Berkeley and Davis; Researcher, USDA and Bureau of Plant Industry; Assistant Dean, College of Agriculture, University of California, Davis (1937-1952).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence and minutes from various commissions, including the National Arboretum and the South Pacific Commission; subject files related to subtropical horticulture and international agriculture; correspondence to academic colleagues and friends.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Ruth Pierce Mine, discovered in 1851, was located in Mariposa County, California, about four miles from the town of Hornitos.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: This small collection contains reports about the mine as well as correspondence regarding a lease option.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Graduate of Stanford University and Stanford Medical School. He headed the Dept. of Pathology at the University of Texas and M.D. Anderson Hospital in Houston, Texas and later the Dept. of Pathology at North Ridge Medical Center in Fort Lauderdale.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Files relating to Russell Ranch in Davis and ranches in Idaho and Arizona. Includes correspondence, financial statements, tax returns, and annual reports.
Photograph of Fred H. Abbot, dairy industry associate connected with the University of California, Davis.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Child psychiatrist who also served on the University of California, Davis' Department of Psychiatry, Volunteer Clinical Faculty from 1970-2003. From 1958-1964, Rudin served as the Deputy Director for Community Services at the California Department of Mental Hygiene.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Materials relating to mental health services in California and the Short-Doyle Act. Present as well are articles, speeches, presentations, and syllabi for courses Rudin taught as Clinical Professor of Psychiatry at UC Davis. Materials relating to his involvement with the Sacramento Area Physicians for Social Responsibility and the United Nations Association of Sacramento are also included.

title.rendered: Royal Arch Masons. Manzanita Chapter No. 29. Ledger.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: North San Juan Chapter of the Royal Arch Masons.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Ledger containing names of members with records of payment of dues, donations, and loans. Also includes death dates for some members.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: M.D., University of California, San Francisco (1914); Staff Allergist at Merritt Hospital, Oakland (1916-retirement); Lecturer, University of California, San Francisco; author of <cite>Bronchial Asthma: Its Diagnosis and Treatment</cite> (1963).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Reprints pertaining to gastroenterology, asthma, cystic fibrosis, emphysema, chronic ulcerative colitis, diabetes, and ulcers of the stomach and mouth. Medical histories, articles, lecture notes, talks, allergy journals, photographs and radiographs.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, research material regarding California's agricultural economics, history, and politics.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Political Science, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Selected manuscripts of Rothchild's conference papers and writings whichfocus on politics and government in Africa.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Raymond F. Roth (1915-1991) spent much of his career working for farm labor programs. After a brief stint from 1941 to 1942 working for the Farm Security Administration, Roth joined the U.S. Navy during World War II. After his return to civilian life, Roth worked in different capacities for the California Department of Employment, Farm Labor Service. His work included the administration of migrant labor and housing programs for U.S. citizens as well as Mexican Nationals in the Bracero Program.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Reference files, publications, and photographic material on the Department of Employment, Farm Labor Service and the Bracero Program. The collection also contains annual reports, speeches, correspondence, memoranda, internal reports and bulletins, financial records, and training manuals. The Military Service series contains both Roth's naval records and his wife Marcella M. Lantz's army records and includes training orders, medical records, transfer and promotion records, certificates, and release documents.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Plant Biology, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material regarding Jojoba; experiment notebooks.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Music, University of California, Davis (1952-1988).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains Rosen's correspondence and notes; teaching materials; compositions, including the operas <cite>Calisto and Melibea</cite> and <cite>Emperor Norton of the USA</cite>; compositions by Rosen's friends and UC Davis colleagues; and a small set of annotated scores from Rosen's personal collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Fourth-generation Yolo County farmer active in agricultural land use and preservation issues; head of the California Department of Food and Agriculture (1977-1982); deputy secretary for the USDA (1993-2000).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, clippings, budget papers, agendas, and meeting notes relating to Rominger's work with the Department of Food and Agriculture; files on pesticides, water appropriation, soil erosion, farm labor, and natural resources.
Manuscript of remarks on poetry by relatives of Peter J. Shields, excerpts from poetry composition books from the 1850's.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Mathematics, University of California, Davis, and statistician at the Experiment Station working closely with enologists.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Lecture notes and articles on the statistical analysis of viticultural data.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Dr. Eleanor Rodgerson (1909-2007) was an obstetrician-gynecologist in private practice in Sacramento, California. She also served on the faculty of the University of California, Davis School of Medicine.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence written while she was a resident at the Chicago Maternity Center, her articles, including those published in <cite>Sacramento Medicine</cite> and <cite>Sierra Sacramento Valley Medicine</cite>, newspaper clippings from her column "Questions Women Ask," a manuscript copy of her autobiography,"The Next Best Thing," travel diaries, and four scrapbooks from vacations taken with her children.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Lecturer of Medieval Studies, Writing, and Humanities Computing, University of California, Davis (1976-2010).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Materials from Roddy's research related to computers and the humanities and the revival of medieval drama in Britain (1951-1969).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Rockwell served as Professor of Psychiatry at the University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: This small collection contains Rockwell's lecture notes as well as several articles he wrote.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of English, University of California, Davis, nature writer, photographer, and teacher of bioregionalism. Researcher and teacher in Bible as literature and literature of nature.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Essays, coursework, correspondence, lectures, notes, exhibit catalogs, reviews, books, photographs, manuscripts, publications and exhibition information, audiotapes, flyers, and posters.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Author of The Wine Press and the Cellar: A Manual for theWine-maker and the Cellar-man.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Scrapbook containing clippings on wine, brandy, raisins,and grapes as well as Rixford's handwritten notes.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Native American Studies, University of California, Davis (1970-1991). Member of the Hupa/Yurok/Karok tribes of Northern California. Dr. Risling helped found D-Q University in 1971. Risling helped launch the Native American Studies program at the University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Files, audiotapes, newspaper clippings, newsletters, reports, memos, legal papers on subject of Native Americans. Includes information about Indian education, Indian law, and Native American Rights Fund (NARF).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Norman E. Riley graduated from UC Davis in 1978. His early photography work focused in the pictorial style and he was active shooting scenes in and around both Davis, California and Sacramento, California. In 1984 he advanced to large format work and thereafter, working in the f/64 style, concentrated on architectural studies and landscapes primarily in the Western United States and in Europe. From 2006 to 2011, Riley turned almost exclusively to still life work.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Small, medium, and large format negatives and selected silver gelatin prints from those film negatives.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Senior lecturer in Chicana/o Studies Program, founder of the National Association for Chicano Studies.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, subject files, curriculum materials, and research materials

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Commercial beekeeper, author of <cite>Honey Plants of California</cite> (1911), and owner of a book store, The Book Den.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, photographs of various apiaries and apiculturalists, and scrapbooks relating to beekeeping, bee diseases, and queen bee breeders.
Black and white photographs; images reproduced from Eastman's Studio.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Horse ranger in the Trinity Alps who guided and packed for Jervie Eastman.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Inventor of a euthanasia device called the "Lethal chamber for the painless extinction of lower animal life."
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence with the Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals and notes on the chamber's use and construction.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: In 2001 Reynoso became the first recipient of the Boochever and Bird Chair for the Study and Teaching of Freedom and Equality at the University of California, Davis School of Law. He served as an associate justice of the California Supreme Court (1982-1987) and Vice Chair of the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights (1993-2004).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Activities files, organization, people and issues files, files on committees and commissions, and correspondence.

title.rendered: Reynolds, Christopher A. Collection of Women’s Song.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Music, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Professor Reynolds has identified and collected sheet music written by women composers active in North America and England between 1850 and 1950. Women often had difficulty in having their works performed by orchestras and professional chamber ensembles, but were able to make a contribution as successful song writers. This collection consists of more than 3000 songs by women. Professor Reynolds' project, "Women Song Composers: A Listing of Songs Published in the United States and the British Commonwealth, ca. 1890-1930" and a searchable database containing references to 15,400 songs by 1580 composers may be found at Merritt, a repository of the California Digital Library. Data includes: composer, title, poet,publishers, cities of publication, years of publication, and accompaniment. The items in Professor Reynolds' Collection of Women Song are being cataloged individually in our online catalog. To search the items that have been cataloged to date, search author = Christopher A. Reynolds Collection of Women's Song. A quick link to that search is provided here.

title.rendered: Revere Copper and Brass, Inc. Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Series of pamphlets bringing architectural concepts and designs to the American public.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Author of <cite>Acoustic design and noise control</cite> (1973) and <cite>Studio Acoustics</cite> (1981).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: One 45 rpm recording of animal noises.
Pamphlets concerning the role of the Christian church in rural farming communities, including papers published by the National Catholic Rural Life Conference.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Painter and illustrator for a variety of wine manufacturers.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Posters, advertising artwork and copy, marketing plans, clippings, and ephemera relating to the wine industry in California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Reed Quicksilver Mine was located in Yolo County, near the common corner of Yolo, Napa, and Lake Counties, about fourteen miles west of Rumsey.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: This small collection contains reports about the mine, several pieces of correspondence, as well as twenty-seven photographs of the mine property.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Reclamation District #551 was an area near Courtland, California set aside by the State wherein marsh lands would be dredged, drained, and converted to farm land.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Four bank ledgers (1893-1922) and four minutes books containing trustee board meeting minutes and financial reports to the district (1893-1945).
Early manuscript draft of a book Raynesford co-authored with Wayne C. Lee, <cite>Trails of the Smoky Hill: From Coronado to the cowtowns</cite> (1980).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Martin Ray was a California winemaker noted for his 100% varietal wines and his efforts to establish a quality control standard for California wines. He purchased the Paul Masson Winery and produced wine there from 1936 to 1942. In 1943 he established his own vineyard on nearby Mt. Eden and produced wines there until 1972. Eleanor Ray was instrumental in marketing the wines, handling public relations, and maintaining the correspondence for the business
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, manuscripts, business files, clippings, public relations files, subject files relating to Quality Control, grape varieties and vintages, and legal files (including litigation documents).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Wildlife Biology, University of California, Davis (1971-1991).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Files from Raveling's Canada Goose Study in Manitoba and Rochester,Minnesota, his research data files, and publications by and about him.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Solomon Ansky (pseudonym of Solomon Rappoport) was a Jewish ethnologist and man of letters whose most renowned work is his play, <cite>The dybbuk</cite>.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Typescript of Ansky's <cite>The devil's sabbath</cite>.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Graduate of the Viticulture and Enology Department of the University of California, Davis, author and composer of Cal Aggie Fight Song, spent his career in wine sales working for Paul Masson and 21 Brands.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, speeches, articles, photographs, notebooks from UCD classes, and materials relating to the production of his book, <cite>The great wine grapes and the wines they make</cite>.

title.rendered: Quire, Joseph H. Papers Relating to Peter J. Shields.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Personal friend of Peter J. Shields.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, articles and ephemera related to Peter J. Shields.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Quinn was a Berkeley businessman and involved with the American Friends Service Committee group working to help local Native Americans. Between the late 1940's and the early 1960's, he toured northwestern California and taped the music of the Hupa, Karuk, and Yurok tribes, among others.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Taped interviews with northwestern Californian Native Americans concerning government programs and the treatment of Native Americans, as well as stories and songs reflecting various Native American cultures.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The founding meeting of the Putah Creek Council took place on Feb. 3, 1988, with the idea of bringing together people who would protect the water level in Putah Creek as well as the creek's remaining riparian habitat.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains materials related to a lawsuit by the Putah Creek Council, UC Davis and the City of Davis against the Solano County Water Agency, Solano Irrigation District, and other Solano entities. The suit, which sought permanent environmental flows for the 23 miles ofPutah Creek below Putah Diversion, resulted in the Putah Creek Accord.

title.rendered: Public Health History of California Collection

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Dvds and transcripts of oral history interviews of 19 persons importantin the history of the California Department of Public Health. Interviewswere conducted between 1986 and 2009.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Evolution and Ecology at the Irvine and Davis campuses of the University of California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, notes, course materials, drafts of papers and book, research materials, and card files related to Timothy Prout's teaching career in evolution and ecology at the University of California, Davis and at the University of California, Riverside.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Geologist for the Bureau of Reclamation, Sacramento, California (1958-1986); author of <cite>Irrigation history of the West-Central San Joaquin Valley-San Joaquin Valley drainage program</cite> (1989) and <cite>Lithology and physical properties of alluvium in the West-Central San Joaquin Valley</cite> (1989).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Bureau of Reclamation reports and memoranda dealing with California's Central Valley Project, including information about engineering geological investigations of several dam sites, canal alignments, land subsidence, hydro compaction, geochemical studies and related features, published writings, slides, and photographs.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Online exhibit

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Pomology, University of California, Davis (1924-1962).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Experiment station reports, laboratory notes, and publications generated during Proebsting's career at the University of California, Davis.
Book collection from a British catholic priory.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Pratt Family were early settlers of California's San Joaquin Valley, ultimately settling on the Stanislaus River near Mariposa, California. The family ran the Zinc House stage coach stop which was located near Stockton on the French Camp Road.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence and diaries related to the early settlement of California's San Joaquin Valley, historical photographs of the Pratt family and of farm machinery and draft notes and tapes used in thedevelopment of Jean Noack Pratt's three books.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Restaurateur, historian and author of <cite>Drake's landing in California: a case for San Francisco Bay</cite> (1973) and <cite>Francis Drake & San Francisco Bay: a beginning of the British Empire</cite> (1974).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, commission work notes, exhibits, newspapers and magazinearticles, publications and speeches, and research project notes relatedto Power's interest in Francis Drake and the San Francisco Bay.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Collector (from age ten) of theatre memorabilia, once described as a "walking repository of theatre history."
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Personal files documenting the careers of primarily American and English actors of the 19th and 20th centuries, but including files on playwrights, theatre managers, and other performing arts personalities. Clippings, photographs, pictures, programs, promotional materials, and other theatre-related memorabilia.

title.rendered: Poultry Producers of Central California Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Headquartered in San Francisco, California, Poultry Producers of CentralCalifornia (PPCC) was organized as an agricultural cooperativeassociation in late 1916 to receive, grade, package, and market eggsreceived from its member-producers.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, interdepartmental memos, reports, publications, andadvertising materials for eggs marketed by the cooperative under thename "Nulaids."

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The book, <cite>Davisville '68: the History and Heritage of the City of Davis, Yolo County, California</cite>, was published in 1968 in commemoration of the 100th anniversary of the founding of Davisville in 1868. As supplement to the book, Joann Leach Larkey wrote a series of articles, Portraits of the Past, which were published in the <cite>Davis Enterprise</cite> from 1969-1973 asa supplement to the book.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: This collection, collected by Phyllis Haig, contains clippings of Larkey's articles which were published in the <cite>Davis Enterprise</cite> from 1969-1973 as a supplement to the book, <cite>Davisville '68</cite>. Topics covered include: early Davis and University history, Davis pioneer families, landmarks, and community life through the years.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Graduate of the University of California, College of Agriculture (1916)
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Album containing photographs including those from his time as a student at the University of California, College of Agriculture (now the University of California, Davis)

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis; author of <cite>Brazil: the land and people</cite> (1968, 1973) and <cite>International communism in Latin America: a history of the movement, 1917-1963</cite> (1964).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Microfilm, notes, and correspondence relating to Poppino's historical research; class lectures and papers.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Cpera conductor.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Sheet music by Popper; songs from Shakespeare's Tempest by Roy Travis.

Board of Directors included postmaster general and director of National Park Service.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: By-laws, Articles of Incorporation, and Directives of Association. Also contains Board of Directors minutes, official correspondence, financial records, special committee records, commemorative souvenirs, photographs, and news releases, and correspondence of vice chairman of Association, Edwin H. Burgess (1959-1976).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Collector of books and ephemeral material relating to Chinese cooking methods.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: A hand-colored menu for a feast at the Imperial Palace Restaurant in San Francisco; watercolor on rice paper; print of the Chinese cooking god; unframed pen and ink; realia.
Bumper stickers, buttons, flyers, ballot tickets, about half late 19th century, half mid-20th century. Local, state, and national levels of government represented.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Environmental Science and Policy, University of California, Davis (1998-2000); conducted research on scorpions and spiders in Baja, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, subject files, and reprints.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Pohler received his PhD in Psychology from the University of Texas, Austin (1980) and served as clinical psychologist at Agnews Developmental Center in San Jose.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Pohler collected documents related to the historicalperspectives of California State Hospitals and Developmental Centers.
Predominantly 19th century printed advertisements announcing theatrical events; cast lists may or may not be included.
Written or printed advertisements posted or otherwise distributed to announce theatrical entertainment, most in 19th century England.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: First City Clerk and City Attorney (1917-1932) for the City of Davis; Yolo County Superior Court Judge (1932-1933).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The papers mainly relate to Plant's Davis legal practice and his work settling the estates of eight citizens of Solano, Yolo, and Sacramento counties in the Superior Courts of those California counties. The majority of the papers are correspondence and legal and financial documents.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Early Native American comedian noted for his polished acting in Old comedy and for his dialect and broken-English parts; member of the Park Theatre, New York, stock company.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Seventeen signed working scripts once the property of Henry Placide.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Pioneer Reduction Company processed gold ore in Nevada City, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Organizational records (by-laws, check stubs, bullion book, and stock certificate register) as well as correspondence regarding the plant's operation.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Pierce Family emigrated from Wisconsin in 1852 and became active in early Davis life. In addition to developing a large grain farm, the family became involved in the almond growing business. The senior George W. Pierce was an early Justice of the Peace and a public administrator; George Pierce, Jr. became president of the California Almond Growers' Exchange and the foremost advocate of Davisville as the location for the University Farm; and Eunice Pierce was a member of the Women's Christian Temperance Union.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Diaries, photographs, family and business records, including those relating to the purchase of the University Farm; legal documents, correspondence, travel guides and pamphlets.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Cotton farmer in Tulare County, California, and one of the leaders in the revolt against the one-variety law for farming cotton.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence and reports relating to cotton farming.

title.rendered: Photographs of the University of California, Davis Campus. Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs of the University of California, Davis campus.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs of Ms. Phillips, her colleagues, buildings, equipment, and projects at Davis, Riverside, and Texas.

Her interest in the sciences led her to attend classes in physics, astronomy, and anatomy; she also studied at George Washington University, where she took classes in English and creative writing and devoted her research efforts to the Bacon- Shakespeare authorship controversy.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Scrapbooks, notes, and ephemera relating to Philip's research concerning the nature of the universe and the Bacon-Shakespeare authorship controversy.

Images of 19th century stage actors/actresses, mostly American and British.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, pamphlets.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Librarian, University of California, Davis, and publisher and editor of <cite>Sipapu</cite>, a serial publication on the alternative press.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence with Gary Snyder and A.D. Winans, among others, andmanuscripts of some of Peattie's works.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Robert C. Pearl (1925-2012) served as Cooperative Extension Specialist with the UC Davis Department of Food Science and Technology.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains biographical information, correspondence, and Pearl's publications as well as materials related to UC Cooperative Extension and the UC Davis Department of Food Science and Technology. Also included are materials related to Pearl's involvement with the Institute of Food Technologists and community organizations such as the Davis Rotary Club.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Council Member, City of Davis (1992-1998); Mayor, City of Davis (1998-2000).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Reports, memos, agendas, clippings, and correspondence created while Partanksy was a Davis City Council Member and Mayor.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Managed the University of California, Davis seed certification center and helped form the California Crop Improvement Association.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Seed Certification material.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Farm machinery researcher with an emphasis on steam traction engines.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Clippings, correspondence, research notes, and articles relating to the history of agriculture and a wide variety of agricultural equipment and technologies.

Correspondence, financial papers, and legal documents regarding patent rights to pantothenic acid and beta-alanine invented jointly by Thomas Jukes, Sidney H. Babcock, Jr., and Bernard R. Baker under the auspices of the University of California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Panama-Pacific International Exposition (P.P.I.E.), held in 1915 in San Francisco, commemorated the opening of the Panama Canal. The City of San Francisco sought the Exposition so that they could show the world that it had recovered from the earthquake and fire of 1906. P.P.I.E. covered circa 300 acres along the bayside Marina district of San Francisco. With the exception of the Palace of Fine Arts, all buildings were temporary. The Exposition was held from February 20 to December 4, and attracted circa 19 million visitors.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The Photographs of the Panama-Pacific International Exposition collection contains photographic glass negatives of the 1915 Panama-Pacific International Exposition taken by the Cardinell-Vincent Company, the official photographers of the Exposition. The photographs shows exhibits from food and agricultural company showing the progress that had been made in these areas rather that the history. Also in the collections are photographs of people who were winners of contests, singers and dancers. One photograph (No. 15493) shows Henry Ford and Thomas Edison looking at an Edison Telegraph.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains correspondence and memorabilia of the Palmer Family. The correspondence, written during the mid to late nineteenth century, discusses the Civil War and family matters in Ohio and South Carolina. Transcriptions of most of the letters are also found in the Papers. The family memorabilia consists of an undated carte de visite and an invitation to a 1911 family reunion.
Over 400 pamphlets on paint and varnish materials and procedures.

title.rendered: Pacific Coast Association of Nurserymen Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Proceedings of the 10th-13th annual meetings.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: American playwright, poet, and pioneer in the experimental off-Broadway theatre, Owens received several Village Voice Obie awards and honors from the N.Y. Critics Circle. Owens' plays and poetry have been translated into numerous languages, and her plays have been presented at festivals in Edinburgh, Avignon, and Berlin.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Books, clippings, correspondence, promotional material, and programs illustrating Owens' writing diversity.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of English and Native American Studies and Director of Creative Writing at the University of California, Davis (2000-2002). Owens wrote fiction about Native American and western environmental themes. His scholarly works focused on John Steinbeck and Native American literature.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscripts of his works, correspondence with publishers and students, course syllabi, reviews and articles on his works, manuscripts, dissertations, and publications by other authors, and videocassettes.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs of people and places in town of Yolo (in Yolo County).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photograph album depicting life in the convent.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Class materials, research notes, articles, and correspondence.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Dean, School of Veterinary Medicine, University of California, Davis (1996-2011).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Dean Osburn's weekly update emails, materials related to the UC Davis School of Veterinary Medicine, the Association of American Veterinary Medical Colleges North American Veterinary Medical Consortium, foreign animal & zoonotic disease, as well as Osburn's research on the bluetongue virus.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Russian actor apprenticed at the Moscow Art Theatre and a member of the Studio; founder of the Theatre of Dramatic Art in Manchuria, following his illegal exit from Russia in the 1930's.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Scripts in Russian by both Russian and European playwrights; some programs, reviews, and slides regarding Russian theatre.

Its purpose was to provide space for exhibitions for professional artists in a non-competitive, supportive environment.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Exhibition announcements, slides of artists' work, and a run of the newsletter, <cite>Inside Art</cite>, published by Open Ring Galleries.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains two DVDs entitled, "My Father Who Art in Nature: John Olmsted Memorial" and "Stories of the Yuba: a Filmmaker's Journey on the River of his Youth, both by Alden Olmsted, the son of John D. Olmsted. There is also a set of slides entitled "The Language of Nature, Set 1, California Plant and Animal Life in 720 Slides, edited by John D. and Priscilla C. Olmsted.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Anthropology, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Articles by Olmsted, manuscript of his book, <cite>A lexicon of Atsugewi</cite>.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Economics, University of California, Davis; Director, Institute of Government Affairs, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Background research materials for an article co-authored by Olmstead and Paul Rhodes, "The agricultural mechanization controversy of the interwar years," which appeared in <cite>Agricultural history</cite> 68:3 (Summer 1994).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Viticulture and Enology, University of California, Davis (1931-1977).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Faculty papers including correspondence, research files, slides on grape varieties, grape variety reports by county, and materials relating to his activities in symposiums, conferences, and advisory boards.
Vineyards' business records.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Poultry Husbandry and Avian Sciences, University of California, Davis (1959-1983). He pioneered research on artificial insemination of turkeys and was a founder of the Raptor Center on campus.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence and publications by Ogasawara.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: California State Secretary of Health and Welfare (1975-1982).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Koda Family is an important Japanese and Japanese-American familythat owned and operated Koda Farms. He was born in 1882 in Ogawa, Japan. Due to his success he was widely known amongst Japanese Americans as the "rice king." During World War II the family was placed in Jerome Relocation Center in Arkansas and at the end of the war transferred to the Granada Relocation Center in Colorado. This was even though the U.S. government ordered that the business be kept running to produce food and fiber. The company was managed by strangers, until the family was released and able to come back to claim their business. Keisaburo's sons, Edward and William "Bill," took over building the business in the post war years, becoming the first commercial growers of sweet rice marketing Sho-Chiku-Bai Sweet Rice andMochiko Blue Star Brand Sweet Rice Flour. They also developed a unique variety of rice called Kokuho Rose. In 1977 Bill Koda sold his share of the business to his brother Edward and was no longer involved in the Koda Family Farm. Today Koda Farm is operated by Edward Koda's direct descendants. The Koda Family Papers are the papers of Bill Koda and his wife, Jean (Morimoto) Koda.
