acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Digitized images from this collection are available on Calisphere

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: News editor for Caterpillar Tractor Company (1927-1933); freelance agricultural journalist (1933-1971).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Brochures, correspondence, manuscripts, clippings, serials, photographs, and posters relating to the development of agricultural machinery in the United States, Canada, and Europe, particularly the history of tractors and combines.
Photographs and postcards of the University of California, Davis campus.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Plant Pathology, University of California, Davis
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Research material, correspondence, reports, handbooks.
Collection of Hertzman's recipes, notes, clippings, journals.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Fred S. Herrington (1898-1971) was a California lawyer who collected menus.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Shipboard and restaurant menus from around the world.

title.rendered: Heringer, Robert P. Recollections of Clarksburg, California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Local historian and native of Clarksburg, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Research essays by Heringer which describe life and early pioneers in the Clarksburg area.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Poet Dianna Henning is the author of <cite> Broken Bone Tongue,</cite> <cite>Song Water Stones and Others: Poems,</cite> and <cite>The Tenderness House.</cite> She worked with the California Poets in the Schools Program and facilitated the Thompson Peak Writers Workshop in Lassen County, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains personal journals, correspondence, and manuscripts of Henning's work. Also included are materials related to her involvement with the California Poets in the School program and receipt of the Event Horizon's Book Award. Correspondents include the following poets: William Matthews, Richard Jackson, Thomas Rain Crowe, Steve Sanfield, Dale Pendell, Marilyn Jurich, and Ioanna Veronika Warwick, among others.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Manager of the International Harvester Company archives for many years.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Notes and memorabilia relating to Henn's affiliation with International Harvester; framed lithograph.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Paul Loyola Henchy (1913-1957) worked for the Southern Pacific Companyin San Francisco.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: 1350 negatives of rural areas of Arizona, California, Colorado, Nevada,New Mexico, and Utah. Included are images of old buildings, mines andmills.
The small collection contains materials from John H. Helwig related to a mining claim for the Jennie Lind Placer Mine in North Bloomfield, California in the late twentieth century.
Notes and drawings relating to fire engines, steam shovels and tractors, bulldozers, and other kinds of agricultural machinery.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Biochemistry, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Hedrick's correspondence and manuscripts, as well as meeting, seminar and conference materials.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Owner and farmer of "The Yolanda," 160 acres of orchard and vineyard, and "The Copa de Oro," 200 acres of alfalfa and grain, in Woodland, California during the early-to-mid 20th century. Hecke was California's first Director of Agriculture, serving from1919-1931.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Personal and business correspondence and one volume of minutes of theCalifornia State Board of Agriculture. Subjects include family news,crop sales, supply orders, ranch workers, and political activity withstate and federal agricultural boards.

title.rendered: Hazen, Harry. Papers on the University Farm

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Harry Edward Hazen (1897-1953) was a 1918 graduate of the University Farm School. After graduation, he became a commercial beekeeper and later founded the Hazen Hardwood Flooring Company in North Hollywood, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection includes Hazen's 1916-1918 scrapbook of University of California Farm photographs and memorabilia, a 1918 Farm Rodeo yearbook, a copy of the booklet "Harry and I at the University Farm," a set of self-bound booklets on apiculture by Swarthmore, Hazen's 1918 diploma from UC College of Agriculture, and two family photographs.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Blog post about the collection

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of English, University of California, Davis (1966-2004).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Small amount of correspondence from his teaching and research including brief letters from Bernard Malamud, Arthur Miller, William Styron, and Somerset Maugham, notes on Ernest Hemingway's works, and three published articles by or about Hemingway.

title.rendered: Hayden, Charles H. and Richard M. Papers

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Charles H. Hayden (1827-1919) and Richard M. Hayden (1841-1936) lived in Callahan's Ranch (now Callahan) in Siskiyou County, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Bills of sale, receipts, and ephemera related to their life and business operations in Callahan's Ranch, California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Short story writer, poet, and novelist. At the height of his career he was considered one of the best-known American writers of the nineteenth century.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Clippings, ephemera, and periodicals containing Harte's works; photographs and picture postcards, several depicting Harte; typescript and holograph letters.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Extension Specialist in Nematology at the University of California, Davis (1959-1984).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Subject files, correspondence, slides, printed material, and articles and speeches by Hart.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: George H. Hart's career at the University of California began in 1917 when he joined the faculty at Berkeley as Professor of Veterinary Science. He came to Davis in 1926 as Professor of Animal Husbandry and Chairman of the Department, a position he held until 1948, when he became Dean of the School of Veterinary Medicine. He retired in 1954.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Biographical information, correspondence, certificates and diplomas, and two photographs. Also included is a scrapbook containing newspaper and popular journal clippings and articles relating to Hart's career in animal husbandry and veterinary medicine.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Harrison became interested in fine bookbinding in the 1930's and apprenticed for a time with master bookbinder Hazel Dreis. For more than four decades, her bookbinding skills enabled her to bind and preserve a number of volumes within the Michael and Margaret B. Harrison Western Americana collection. In September, 1990, the preservation department of the General Library of the University of California at Davis was dedicated in her honor.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material catalogs and samples, invoices and expense ledgers, clippings, correspondence, and journals relating to fine bookbinding.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Senior Agronomist for the U.S. Department of Agriculture (1934-1952); in charge of the cotton field station in Shafter, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Serials, trade publications, clippings, photographs, and speeches relating to cotton breeding, with an emphasis on the development of the Acala variety.
Memoirs of Howard Harris which document his involvement in the 4-H, the San Benito County Farm Bureau, and San Benito County land and water issues.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Founded in Stockton, California in 1902 by George Harris, the Harris Manufacturing Company began as a small harvester repair shop and eventually expanded into one of California's leading developers of gas harvesters.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Typescript biography of George Harris, founder of the Harris Manufacturing company, by Clifford W. Koster, plus a photocopy of The history of Harris combined header and thresher (1994).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Berkeley (1928-1968).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photostats, microfilm, and research notes relating to commercial shipping in the British colonial ports in North America.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Union activist.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Files from Harer's involvement with the International Longshore and Warehouse Union; clippings on the Vietnam War and North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA); also contains audiocassettes and reel-to-reel tapes.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Political Science, University of California, Davis (1965-1976); author of <cite>Presidential power and accountability: towards a new Constitution</cite> (1974).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence related to research, published and unpublished, dealing with the U.S. Constitution and constitutional reform politics. General subject files also contain materials on agricultural politics, including marketing, price support, and production controls as administered by the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: One of the first beekeepers to import bees into California and inventor of innovative beehives and new methods of rearing queen bees; author of <cite>An improved system of propagating the honey bee</cite> (1860) and <cite>The beekeepers' directory</cite> (1861).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Daybooks documenting Harbison's beekeeping activities; correspondence to and from his brothers, his patent representatives, and business partners; and deeds, business receipts and patent grants.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Considered one of the foremost plant breeders in the country.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, articles, catalogs, notes, photographs, reports, slides.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Associate in the Agricultural Experiment Station and Professor in Truck Crops, University of California, Davis (1938-1967); inventor of the "square" tomato.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence with colleagues regarding tomato breeding activities.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: American actor and stage manager, whose first public stage appearance was at the Astor-Place Opera House in New York in 1850; stage manager at the Boston Theater and the Howard Atheneum in Boston, and the Winter Garden and Wallack's Theater in New York City.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Autographed prompt books for the farce <cite>Bamboozling</cite> and for the melodrama <cite>The bear hunters</cite>, once the property of actor Joseph Hanley.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: National Park Service Ranger and naturalist
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Slides of National Parks and Monuments.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: John Alvin Hall (b. circa 1835) lived in Nevada City, California in the 1860s.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Five letters between various members of the Hall Family, several receipts, a carte de visite of Edward W. Hall, and a handwritten family record of Sargent Hall and Nancy Clay. The 1864 letter from George Hall discusses his enlistment in the 35th Regiment, Massachusetts Infantry and the regiment's subsequent activities in the United States Civil War.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Sacramento, California jurist, amateur historian. Halbert was a director of Pony Express Centennial Association (1957-1961). He was administrator of many Association projects including creation of trail markers.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Halbert's correspondence, speeches, and writings on the Pony Express. The collection also contains clippings, maps, memorabilia, and photographs pertaining to the activities of the Pony Express Centennial Association.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Milton "Hal" Halberstadt, owned and operated M. Halberstadt Illustration Photography Studio in San Francisco from 1945-1973. He specialized in advertising photography and created campaigns for Del Monte Foods, Foremost Brands, Spice Islands, Dole, Raisin Growers Association, Paul Masson Vineyards, among others. After closing the studio in 1973, he taught photography at the University of California, Berkeley, San Francisco State and the University of Oregon.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs, proofs, transparencies, and negatives of Halberstadt's work. Commercial and business correspondence related to photography, business ledgers and records, and teaching documents and notes.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Digitized images from this collection are available on Calisphere

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Water Science, University of California, Davis (1948-1987).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Writings, teaching files including class lecture notes and backgroundmaterials, as well as subject files which contain materials on topicssuch as the peripheral canal and Delta water management. The collectionprovides documentation of the politics of California's water in the latetwentieth century.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: University of California, Berkeley graduate (1912); Harvard Law School (1915); Vice President and Chair, Bank of California, San Francisco branch (1921-1953). The Hackett family donated Yolo County ranch land to the University.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, manuscripts, photographs, books, business records, clippings, legal papers, scrapbooks, photo albums, ephemera, and realia.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Viticulture and Enology, University of California, Davis (1939-1977).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscripts, correspondence, pamphlets, and clippings pertaining to wine and brandy technology, including distillation, refrigeration, biochemistry of alcoholic fermentation, and aging processes.

title.rendered: Gullan, Penny J. Slides on Insect Control

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Penny Gullan served as Professor  of Entomology at the University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains slides with accompanying audio cassettes and text for "Of Ants and Men and Mealybugs," a presentation on insect control in pineapple fields.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Geography and Nutrition, University of California, Davis (1976-2007).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains correspondence, teaching, service, and advising materials, as well as research materials. Also included are materials related to Grivetti's research on the history of chocolate and the book, <cite>Chocolate: History, Culture, and Heritage</cite> (2009) that Grivetti edited with Howard Shapiro.
Photographs of the University of California, Davis campus and student life.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Geography, University of California, Davis (1960-1990). His research focused on the impact of the physical and social environment on the economic activities of different populations.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material regarding Gregor's research on "agrargeography," correspondence, course materials, slides.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Co-author of <cite>A directory of California wine growers and wine makers in 1860</cite> (1967) and <cite>Winemaking in California</cite> (1954).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Twenty fictional essays written by Greenleaf.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Bachelor's degree from the College of Agriculture, University of California, Berkeley (1923). Greene supervised and organized agricultural operations for various institutions and produced and directed films promoting agriculture in California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs, newspaper clippings, lectures, correspondence, radio scripts, and films.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: View digitized films from the Henry Dart Greene Papers on the Internet Archive

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscripts and proofs for Green's novel, <cite>Allegiance</cite> (1983).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Reporter for the <cite>Modesto Bee</cite> and the <cite>Sacramento Bee</cite>.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Background materials supporting Gray's work on various water projects, including the Don Pedro Dam, Hetch Hetchy, the Central Valley Project, the Folsom-South Canal, the Auburn and New Melones Dams, and other issues relating to the Modesto and Turlock Irrigation Districts.

Ephemera relating to various events in California history including the San Francisco earthquake, the opening of the Golden Gate Bridge, the Panama Pacific International Exposition, and the Golden Gate International Exposition.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Biological and Agricultural Engineering, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material regarding cucumber and tomato harvesters.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Office files, grant applications, and professional correspondence; articles, clippings, and microfilm relating to American colonial history; research files for Goodman's book, <cite>Towards a Christian republic: Antimasonry and the great transition in New England, 1826-1836</cite>, minutes and meeting notes relating to Goodman's participation in the American Federation of Teachers, Local 2023.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Environmental Planning, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Environmental planning and management files; books, manuscripts, and research reports regarding open space preservation, recreation planning, and urban horticulture; public service files, including draft legislation; correspondence.
Material regarding pomology; photographs, scrapbooks.

The collection contains thirty-one letters written between 1899-1917.The majority of the letters are to Lydia Vineyard Gleason (1877-1966)from her husband Elmer Percy Gleason (1875-1935). The letters discusstheir courtship, family news, as well as life in Northern California atthe turn of the twentieth century.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Davis, California resident during the 1955 flood.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Clippings, slides, and photographs of Sutter County flood damage in 1955.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Grain dealer in Ohio, in the late 19th century.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Incoming correspondence, fragmentary receipts, market reports, and two brief account ledgers relating to the wholesale grain business, including futures trading, in Ohio.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: English artist-craftsman, engraver, and book illustrator.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Three signed proofs: The Aldine Bible, "St. Matthew," Vol. I; "St. Luke," Vol. II; "Apocalypse," Vol. IV.

title.rendered: Gibson, Robin and Luis Veiga Living Theatre Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professional photographers and former members of The Living Theatre who left the company in 1975 to join a Pittsburgh group, Direct Action Theatre.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs, scripts, and ephemera relating the Living Theatre's Pittsburgh premiere production of <cite>The Money Tower</cite>. Also included are photographs of the Living Theatre's Pittsburgh productions of <cite>Turning the Earth</cite> and <cite>Seven Meditations on Political Sado-Masochism</cite>.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Chinese and Japanese, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Over 350 Chinese films, some subtitled, in a variety of formats; Chinese film posters and film journals.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: University of California cooperative extension cotton farming advisor for Tulare County.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Documents relating to the growth and development of the cotton farming industry.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Poet laureate of California; author of <cite>California Poems</cite> (1966) and <cite>Brief Candle: A Novel</cite> (1987). State Assemblyman (1958-1966).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Garrigus' diary, entitled An American Journal (unpublished).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Sales manager for Yuba Manufacturing Company and Caterpillar Tractor Company.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Printed material and photographs of Caterpillar tractors and Yuba dredges.

title.rendered: Gardner, M.E. Scrapbook of Atomic Energy & Related Subjects.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Physics, University of California, Davis. (1937-1968).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Scrapbook containing newspaper clippings on atomic bombs and atomic energy.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Grandson of Daniel Best.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Best Manufacturing Company photograph albums and patent books.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Papers, photographs, and architectural drawings related to dairy processing in California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Ernest F. Gallo (1916-2010) was a California dairyman and dairy industry consultant from the mid-1930s to the late 1970s.
By-laws from various California fruit growers associations.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Chemistry, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Course notes and timeline of chemistry at the University of California, Davis.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Fried (1924-2007) was a doctor of internal medicine for the VeteransAdministration in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Fried collected an estimated 50,000 wine labels. The collection containsextensive labels from Europe (France, Italy, and Spain) as well as fromthe United States.
Correspondence between military figures involved in the French Revolution; includes manuscripts, reports, accounts, pamphlets, and proposals.

title.rendered: Freeman, Sanford and Barbara. Collection of Henrique Vivian Messetti Materials.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Incoming correspondence of Henrique Vivian Messetti, a writer, performer, and member of a vaudeville-circus family active during the 1920's-1940's. .

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Entomology, University of California, Berkeley (1914-1924); Chair, Division of Entomology, University of California, Davis (1924-1935); Assistant to the Dean of the College of Agriculture, University of California, Davis (1935-1952); Provost, University of California, Davis (1952-1958); and Chancellor, University of California, Davis (1958-1959).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence (1927-1931), subscription requests, and account records pertaining to the Pan-Pacific Entomological Society during Freeborn's tenure as treasurer; notebook containing illustrations of insects; Agricultural Experiment Station reports (1927-1935) on insect control studies.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Research Entomologist at the University of California, Berkeley (1943-1974). After his retirement from Berkeley he worked in the Nematology Department at the University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Research notes and photographs from Frazier's career at UC Berkeley and UC Davis.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Professor of Zoological Medicine, University of California, Davis (1958-1991).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Conference materials, articles, drafts of textbook chapters, correspondence, and subject files related to Fowler's career in zoological medicine.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: In April 1898, Herbert George Fowler was enrolled as a Corporal of Company L of the First Regiment of the Illinois Infantry Volunteers to serve two years or the duration of the Spanish American War. He was discharged from service on November 17, 1898.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Twenty-one letters written during the time of the Spanish American War. Written from April 30, 1898 to August 11, 1898, they detail the movements of Fowler's Company from camps in Springfield, Illinois to Chickamauga, Georgia to Picnic Island in Tampa, Florida and eventually to action in the trenches at Santiago. In the letters he describes the living conditions of the soldiers, the sickness that spread through the camps, his daily schedule, training exercises, the landscape, and the weather.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: James Forbes (1871-1938), a twentieth century playwright, authored The Chorus Lady, The Commuters, and The Famous Mrs. Fair.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains manuscripts, correspondence, clippings, photographs, and memorabilia related to a number of his works.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Native American Studies and Anthropology, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Articles, reports, monographs, serials, microfilm and photographs relating to Native American History, civil rights, ethnic studies and Native American education. Contains Native American serials from the 1970s and 1980s. There is also a small, but complete, photographic survey of electric railroad cars in Los Angeles, California, and the West Coast.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Attorney (solicitor) in Plymouth, England; Labor member of Parliament (1922-1924 and 1929-1935); Secretary of Mines in the Labor Cabinet (1931-1932); authority on Oliver Cromwell and president of the Cromwellian Society.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, receipts, newspaper clippings, and book reviews pertaining to Foot's scholarly and collecting interests.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Art and Art History, University of California, Davis, researched and published on T'ang Tomb murals outside China.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Notes for her dissertation <cite>Secular Figure Painting of the T'ang Dynasty</cite> as well as research materials relating to Chinese art.
University of California, Davis student's classnotes.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Associate of the Humanities Institute at the University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence and manuscript material of Mala Lasser, a German Jewish writer of the 1930s and 1940s and refugee to England. Materials are in English and German and focus on social criticism.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Cooperative Extension Specialist in Wildlife Enhancement, University of California, Davis (1980-2004).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Subject files, research materials, course syllabi, and correspondence relating to his research in wildlife population and habitat management.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Community and Rural Sociology, Washington State University.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains research materials related to Fiskeâ€™s doctoral dissertation, <cite>The College and its Constituency: Rural and Community Development at the University of California, 1875-1978.</cite> Also included are materials related to the lawsuit by the California Agrarian Action Project against the Regents of the University of California regarding agricultural mechanization research. In addition, the collection contains two audiocassettes and a transcript of a 1978 talk at UC Davis by Paul S. Taylor, Professor of Economics at UC Berkeley.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Woodland, California family.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The majority of the collection consists of incoming correspondence to Edna Fisher (1870-1962). Primary correspondents are Ernest Blake, a cousin, and Adella Fisher (1867-1952), Edna's sister. From 1888 to 1889, Adella served as a primary school teacher in Winters, California, during which time she wrote many letters to her sister. The correspondence details family matters and the daily activities of the correspondents. Descriptions of news and life in Yolo County, California are also included.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Close friend of Maynard A. Amerine.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, photographs, videotapes, clippings.
Copy of the "Firestone Farm Guide Book" annotated with the anonymous owner's accounts.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Firehouse Theatre was founded in Minneapolis in 1963 as an avant-garde theatre company, and moved to San Francisco in 1969. Dedicated to experimental theatre with new staging techniques, they produced works by Jack Gelber, Megan Terry, Sam Shepard, and Jean-Claude Van Itallie, among others.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, films, photographs, promotional materials, and workshop notebooks documenting the history of the Firehouse Theatre from its beginnings in Minnesota to its residence in San Francisco.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Western correspondent for the Scripps-Howard Newspaper Alliance; covered the Teapot Dome Oil scandal, monitored the passage of the Boulder Canyon Project Act, and investigated corruption in the electric and gas utilities industry. Nominated for the Pulitzer Prize in 1931.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Materials relating to Finney's career as a newspaper reporter, including correspondence, scrapbooks, diaries, manuscripts, clippings, photographs, research materials, legal documents, and personal mementos. Also contains her unpublished autobiography, <cite>Journey From the Star</cite>, and her unpublished history of Downieville, California, <cite>Rogues and Riches</cite>.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Blog post about the collection

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Examples of small and alternative presswork and typography, including advertisements, broadsides, and postcards.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Editor of the <cite>Sacramento Union</cite> from 1962-1966. After Finder left the Sacramento Union, he devoted his time to lecturing and teaching, primarily at the Extension Program of the University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: An unfinished manuscript of Finder's unpublished book, <cite>Reflections inAsia</cite>, written following a world tour in 1966.
Cigar bands and cigar box labels.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: D.M. Ferry Company of Detroit, Michigan, merged with the C.C. Morse Company of San Jose, California, in 1930 to create the Ferry-Morse Seed Company, now headquartered in Modesto, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Company ledgers (1879-1946), advertising posters (1890-1918), original art work (1896-1906), photographs, realia, and sales notebooks (1910-1950).
Manuals, catalogs, and brochures relating to equipment used in enology, brewing, and distillation.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Jay Feldman is the author of <cite>When the Mississippi Ran Backwards: Empire, Intrigue, Murder, and the New Madrid Earthquakes</cite> (2005),  <cite> Suitcase Sefton and the American Dream</cite> (2006), <cite>Manufacturing Hysteria: A History of Scapegoating, Surveillance, and Secrecy in Modern America</cite> (2011), and <cite>Hitting: An Official Major League Baseball Book</cite> (1991).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Research materials for Feldman's books <cite>When the Mississippi Ran Backwards: Empire, Intrigue, Murder, and the New Madrid Earthquakes</cite> and <cite>Manufacturing Hysteria: A History of Scapegoating, Surveillance, and Secrecy in Modern America.</cite> The collection also includes audio tapes of oral histories of Japanese Americans.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: A project of the Works Progress Administration, the Federal Theatre Project provided socially useful jobs for needy professional theatre people.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Jervie Henry Eastman was born, July 20, 1880, in White Cloud, Michigan. His family moved to northern California in 1886. In 1898, Eastman launched his photographic career in Sisson, California (later named Mount Shasta), as a view photographer. He became a partner in the Shasta View Company in 1907. Eastman lost his entire stock of plates and cards in a fire in 1912.In 1921, Jervie Henry Eastman moved to Susanville and established Eastman & Company as a commercial photography and post card studio. In 1936 he hired Mirl Simmons, a young photographer from Hillsborough, West Virginia, to help with the postcard photography. In 1947, Eastman and Simmons became partners. The business had expanded to provide photographic supplies to southeastern Oregon and studios in Westwood, Weed, and Susanville.Eastman retired from photography in 1959 and sold his share of the business to Simmons. He died in Susanville on February 11, 1969.Simmons ran the Eastman Studios until 1980, when he retired and sold the business to John and Shirley Castle. Mirl Simmons died on April 27, 1987, in Jamestown, California.The Eastman's Originals Collection (the historical postcards and negatives) was sold to Anne Fisher in 1982. She managed the collection until her retirement in 1994. She donated the collection to the University of California, Davis, in 1994.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Photographs, negatives, and postcards for a wide variety of northern California locations and events, including dam construction, logging, mining, food processing, and community buildings and activities.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Theatrical-literary agent based in New York City from 1957 to 1976; among Cole's clients were Saul Bellow, Bertolt Brecht, Zero Mostel, Luigi Pirandello, and Sam Shepard.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Business and financial records, correspondence, legal documents, photographs, programs, promotional materials, and scripts documenting Cole's activities.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Blog post about the collection

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Extension Specialist, Asst. Secretary of the USDA
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Publications written by Coke and others.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Comparative Drama, University of California, Davis (1972-1992).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains one folder of correspondence to and from Ruby Cohn concerning theater and literature.

The John F. Clewe Correspondence contains outgoing, incoming, and third party letters which span the years 1925-1958. The majority of the letters are between Clewe and his sister Marie and Clewe and Marie's husband Trevenen J. Taylor, a technician in the Division of Veterinary Medicine at the University of California, Davis. Correspondence with Trevenen Taylor discusses marketing a 16mm Kodachrome film created by Taylor which was able to record the emergence of the Monarch butterfly, detailing the butterfly's development from caterpillar to the adult stage. Correspondence with Marie Taylor discusses Clewe family matters.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: John Cleveland's family were neighbors of the parents of Horace Greeley. After learning the printer's trade, he obtained a place on the <cite>New York Tribune</cite>, which had been founded by Greeley three years before. In 1846 he married Mr. Greeley's sister Esther. He was at different times Albany correspondent of the <cite>Tribune</cite>, editor of the weekly and semi-weekly editions, and news editor.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Letters from Horace Greeley to Cleveland.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Anthropology, University of Denver
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Pamphlets, correspondence, newspapers, and organizational material relating to Clemmer's activities with the Friends of the Hopi and the Committee of Concern for Traditional Indian Land and Life. Topics include Black Mesa Mining and Power Plants, problems with the Bureau of Indian Affairs, and land claims.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Bicycle racer, collector, and enthusiast of the sport.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Bicycling books, journals, trade publications and directories, racing programs, rule books, posters, comics and other materials relating to bicycling.
Maps of Davis, California.

Correspondence, property assessment records, legal opinions, bids, receipt books for business licenses, contracts, newsletters, bulletins, maps, plans, personnel recommendations, a warrant register, a registry of births, policy statements, regulations, petitions, meeting minutes, tax returns, court decisions, and election documents for the city of Davis, California. Also included is the personal correspondence file of Norman D. Thomas, the city's third clerk and city attorney, serving at the height of the Great Depression.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Circle in the Square Theatre was founded in 1951 in New York City by Theodore Mann, JosÃ© Quintero, Jason Wingreen, Eileen Cramer and Emily Stevens.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Fifty-four photographs depicting the 1952 Circle in the Square production of Tennessee Williams' <cite>Summer and Smoke</cite>, directed by Jose Quintero.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Manufacturer of meat packing equipment.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material regarding supply business operations; Accounts, blueprints, catalogs.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Actor, teacher, principal director with the San Francisco Mime Troupe (1967-2003)
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Materials from his involvement with the San Francisco Mime Troupe and files relating to his theater projects in Asia.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Former graduate student of Geology, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Class notes.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Socialist activist
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material regarding socialism; articles, correspondence, mailing lists, memos.
Photographs, newspaper clippings about former Chinese Communists of 1950s

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Chinese Nationalist Party (Kuomintang) of Sacramento was founded in 1920 to support the effort of the nationalist movement led by Chiang Kai-shek.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Pamphlets, photographs, correspondence, and posters regarding the Chinese Nationalist Party of Sacramento.
Two Chinese fans hand painted by Tung Kao, with poems in calligraphy by Juan Yuan and Chi Huang.
Photographs depicting U.S. military maneuvers, equipment, facilities, and ceremonies in Hawaii; political torture photographs from China.
Typescript of The Coachella Valley: agriculture and flood and earthquake hazards (1953).
Long-playing records which feature Chicano music. Artists include Lola Beltran, Yolanda Del Rio, Pedro Infante, Flaco Jimenez, Luis Perez Meza, Augustine Ramirez, and Silvestre Vargas, among others.
Advertisements on silk material for various Yolo County enterprises.
Photographs of the University of California Davis campus and the surrounding area. Also included are several photographs of Picnic Day 1936.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Rosemary Chan, born December 16, 1921 in Suisun, California. She was a teacher, traveler and philanthropist. She was very active in the Square and Circle Club of San Francisco, a Chinese woman's culture.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection consists of photographs of family and travels throughout the world and information about the Square and Circle Club of San Francisco.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Manager of the Brno, Czechoslovakia Trade Fairs and Exhibitions.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Wine labels, price lists, menus, advertising brochures, and clippings relating to wine from throughout the world, with an emphasis on Eastern Europe. Pamphlets, regional wine maps, and labels, arranged by country, are excellent graphic resources. Subjects files include materials on corkscrews, fermentation science, labeling, toasts, patents, wine and poetry, and a variety of other topics.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Joann Louise Cohn (b. ca. 1930-) attended high school in Portland, Oregon during the mid to late 1940s. Cohn and Gary Snyder became friends in 1946 when they were both teenagers.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Letters from Gary Snyder to the then Joann Cohn, Snyder's poems and journal entries, and a small number of photographs and clippings.
Blueprints for the Caterpillar 20 tractor.
Oral history tapes relating to the technology and culture of tobacco growing.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Author of <cite>Hard rain falling</cite> (1965), <cite>Blade of light</cite> (1966), <cite>Getting off</cite> (1971), <cite>The class of '49</cite> (1985) and <cite>From a distant past</cite> (1988), among other works.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Letters to Carpenter from Gary Snyder, Philip Whalen, Michael McClure, and other contemporary poets.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Entomology, University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscript of The 1989-90 medfly outbreak in Southern California: a chronology of newspaper clippings, letters, memos and testimonies (1990).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Plant Pathology at the University of California, Davis (1959-1993).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Ninety-three 35mm slides, most of which were taken by Campbell, duringhis academic career. Subjects include: campus scenes, people,agricultural machinery and practices, and the Central Valley.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Plant Pathology, University of California, Davis (1959-1993).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, notes, and reprints related to Campbell's work as Professor of Plant Pathology.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Mrs. Patrick Campbell (1865-1940), a British actress, performed in <cite>TheHunchback</cite>, <cite>The School for Scandal</cite>, <cite>As You Like It</cite>, and <cite>The Second Mrs.Tanqueray</cite>, among other plays.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Prompt scripts, working scripts, and other production materials relating to three plays: <cite>The moon of Yamato</cite> by Robert d'Humiere; <cite>The Macleans of Bairness</cite> by Edith Littleton; and <cite>Madame Kuranda</cite> by Frederick Horace Rose.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Nineteenth century clothmaker and print designer.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence and instructions regarding printing and dying materials and tool construction; examples of calico print designs and materials.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Peter Camejo (1939-2008), third-party political activist, helped found the California Green Party in 1991. He ran for California Governor in 2002, 2003, and 2006; as independent Ralph Nader's vice presidential running mate in the 2004 presidential election; and as the Socialist Workers Party presidential candidate in 1976.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Camejo's journals, correspondence, writings, and audiovisual materials.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Founded in 1860, the CWGA is an organization of sheep breeders and producers. The mission of the CWGA is to help producers to increase profits and efficiencies.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Lists of officers and directors, board of directors meetings and speeches, financial statements, membership report, stenographic reports of the annual convention, correspondence, convention and banquet programs.
Copy prints and original photographs of California State Fair exhibits, circa 1919-1925.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The California State Beekeepers Association was organized in 1889 toserve the beekeeping industry in California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Meeting minutes, correspondence, financial records, annual conventionprograms, publications, realia and photographs.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Originally formed in 1965 in the east bay region, the California Native Plant Society (CNPS) is a statewide non-profit organization of amateurs and professionals with a common interest in California's native plants.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Organization records including photocopies of correspondence, membership records, newsletters, notes, news clippings, publications, and photographs. Also includes a small amount of material related to the Native Plant Society of New Mexico.

title.rendered: California Lima Bean Growers Association. Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Material about the Assocation's formation/history.

title.rendered: California League of Food Processors Archives.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Established in 1905, the California League of Food Processors is a state trade association representing canners, freezers, hydrators, and dried fruit packers who produce canned and frozen fruits and vegetables. The organization monitors political activities affecting members, and works with government agencies in development of product standards.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Financial records, Board of Directors minutes, background information on processing regulations, and some records of other entities, such as the California Olive Growers Association.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Formed in 1957 with capital contributions from California fruit and vegetable growers, the California Canners and Growers Cooperative processed, distributed, and marketed its members' crops. It was the largest company of its kind in the U.S. and, at one time, controlled 65% of the nation's diet canned fruit market. The company declared bankruptcy in 1983.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Invoices, cash receipts, accounts receivable and payable ledgers, financial statements, payroll ledgers, bids, marketing studies, canceled checks, pricing analysis, inventories, correspondence, and monthly manager's letters. Legal files pertaining to the lawsuit filed against the U.S. Government for remuneration for inventory destroyed after the August, 1970 ban on products containing cyclamates.

title.rendered: California Association of the American Registry of Professional Entomologists. Records

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: A voluntary, non-profit association of California resident members of the American Registry of Professional Entomologists whose purpose was to enhance the contributions of professional entomologists to the people of California and to society.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Organizational records related to the foundation and operations of the California Association of the American Registry of Professional Entomologists. Includes correspondence, membership records, financial records, bylaws, brochures, newsletters, and photographs.

title.rendered: California Agricultural Teaching Aid Photograph Collection.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains mounted photographs used presumably by the Alameda County Schools Curriculum Materials Center and later by the Hayward Unified School District as a teaching tool. The photographs are related to three subjects: dairy farming, the Delta Mendota Canal Fish Diversion Facility, and cattle ranching in Alameda County.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: View digitized images on California

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Charles M. Silva (1823-1894) and his son Edward B. Silva (1854-1952) operated C.M. Silva & Son, a nursery specializing in fruit trees and plants, in Newcastle, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: 135 letters written to C. M. Silva & Son from 1874-1879. Also included is one volume of outgoing correspondence from July to December 1886. The correspondence discusses growing fruit trees and plants, orders for their fruit and plant stock, shipping procedures, the quality of their products, and account debits and credits.

Seven scrapbooks containing newsclippings regarding agriculture,weather, irrigation, water rights, and agricultural shipping. Theclippings are from publications such as Pacific Rural Press, SacramentoRecord Union, and other Central Valley newspapers.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Agricultural Extension Agent, University of California (1914-1955); Garden Editor, <cite>Oakland Tribune</cite> (1955-1960); past President, California Horticultural Society.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscripts, research material, and photographs on the history of horticulture in California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Lester Burnett (1804-1870) settled in Yuba County, California in 1850. His son Wellington Burnett (1829-1907) served as city and county attorney of San Francisco.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains correspondence related to Lester, his wife Olive, and their son Wellington, as well as other Burnett family members. Also included in the collection are legal and financial documents connected to the family.

title.rendered: Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms Archives: Wine Bottle Labels.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms, a department of the U.S. Treasury, licenses U.S. wineries for operation and regulates the labeling of foreign and domestic wine and spirits.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Wine labels and label permit applications submitted by domestic dealers, wineries, or importers to the BATF for approval. Information required on the label includes winery or distillery name and location, type of beverage, content, name of importer or distributor, and in the case of wines, vintage year.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Author of <cite>Plow Peddlar</cite> (1992).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Columns written by Buescher for <cite>Antique Power, Belt Pulley, Famers Advance</cite> and <cite>Old Allis News</cite>.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Moses Brown (October 2, 1742-February 9, 1827), prominent merchant and citizen of Newburyport, Massachusetts, developed a large foreign and domestic trade, especially in sugar, molasses and distilled rum.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Records relating to Brown's involvement in the rum industry in the eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. Included are account statements, invoices, correspondence, and distillery house orders.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Pomology at University of California, Davis (1949-1979).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains several examples of Brown's writings including a typescript of the first volume of his history of the Department of Pomology (1984) and a talk he gave at Apple Day (1967).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Senior irrigation engineer for Western Farm Credit Bank.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Engineering reports on water entities in Arizona, California, Nevada, and Utah prepared for Western Farm Credit Bank to determine the advisability of mortgage lending.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Agricultural Engineering, University of California, Davis (1931- 1962).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, typescripts, notes, and reprints pertaining to Brooks' teaching and agricultural engineering research at the University of California, Davis.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis (1967-1993).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, essays, teaching materials, ephemera, and other materials related to Dr. Brody's time as Professor of History at UC Davis and other academic institutions.
Manuscript of Reminiscences of E. D. Pierce, discoverer of gold in Idaho, relating the story of Irish immigrants in California.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Edmund Breese performed in numerous plays in the United States andLondon and later starred in Hollywood films.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Twenty-four handwritten sides of roles performed by Breese. Sides aredefined as pages containing an actor's part and cue words.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: An alternative theatre group founded in 1961 by Peter Schumann, the Bread and Puppet Theatre relied more on the use of enormous and visually striking puppets than on dialogue to make its anti-establishment statements.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Business correspondence, photographs, promotional materials, and texts of original plays.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of History, University of California, Davis
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Collection contains research materials for Brantley's books, <cite>The Giriama and Colonial Resistance in Kenya, 1800-1920</cite> and <cite>Feeding Families: African Realities and British Ideas of Nutrition and Development in Early Colonial Africa</cite>, as well as materials from the year Brantley spent in Nigeria (1966-1967).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Nelle U. Branch was librarian of the University Farm (now UC Davis) from 1924-1951.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: One small box of recipes.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Collector of catalogs, lists, and other documents pertaining to wine merchants and antiquarian booksellers. He also collected restaurant menus and wine labels.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Collection includes wine labels, buyers' guides, bibliographies, directories, wine lists, menus, antiquarian booksellers' catalogs. It consists mostly of wine catalogs, some of which date back to 1835, and wine labels (over 50,000) with vintages back to 1790. It also includes notes on wines, and the people and events surrounding the wine industry.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Animal Science, University of California, Davis (1957-1993).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Records for the sheep flocks at UC Davis and the Hopland Field Station, his publications, travel diaries, and subject files relating to his research on sheep breeding and genetics.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Lewis Leonard Bradbury (circa 1823-1892), originally from Bangor, Maine, moved to Rosario, (Sinaloa) Mexico in the early 1860s. He began accumulating shares in the "Tajo" mines, eventually gaining controlling interests in 1873. Around 1883, he acquired Rancho Azusa de Duarte in southern California which is now part of the present-day cities of Duarte and Bradbury (both incorporated in 1957) in Los Angeles County, California. Lewis Bradbury, Junior (circa 1881-1948) assumed control of the family business in 1902, and the Bradbury Estate Company was incorporated in 1904. The Estate Company was dissolved in 1965.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Personal and legal materials of the Bradbury family as well as business documents and records pertaining to the family's estate and subsidiary companies in both California and in Mexico. Also found in the collection are documents related to various properties prior to their acquisition by the Bradbury Estate Company.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: Online exhibit

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Block prints made by Henry Evans and Edmund E. Simpson.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Owner of a northern California company, Born and Company, specializing in the irradiation of foods, cold sterilization, and algae production.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Reports, pamphlets, and clippings relating to experiments in the irradiation of strawberries, potatoes, and poultry, and experiments on algae production as a potential cattle protein source.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Anne Bonner Glasscock, writing under the name Michael Bonner, published four novels of Western fiction from 1960-1966.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Outlines, characterizations, typescripts with annotations and revisions, and galleys for four novels, including <cite>Kennedy's gold</cite> (1960); <cite>The iron noose</cite> (1961); <cite>The shadow of a hawk</cite> (1963); and <cite>The disturbing death of Jenkin Delaney</cite> (1966).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: The Boniface family settled in the Capay Valley in 1893.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Untitled history of the Central Valley area, covering the late 19th century, concerning agriculture, pioneers, and Native Americans in the area.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Entomology, University of California, Davis (1946-1979).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Biographical materials, writings, research materials, and correspondencewith researchers, growers, and museums regarding the control ofmosquitoes and other pests, loans and identifications of specimens,publications, and other topics.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: John Bodger and Sons Company, founded in 1890 in California, was a breeder and producer of flower seeds. Bodger Seeds Ltd, a division of the company, was responsible for breeding and production operations. In 2009, the Bodger Company sold its holdings. During its history, Bodger had operating sites in locations in California at Santa Paula, Los Angeles, Gardena, South El Monte, Lompoc, Covina, Chino and also in Chile at Quillota.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Company catalogs and price lists, press releases, black and white negatives, prints, slides, and scrapbooks.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Contemporary American poet and writer; works include <cite>The light around the body</cite> (1967), <cite>Talking all morning</cite> (1980), and <cite>Iron John</cite> (1990), among others.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Four audiotaped radio shows of Bly's lectures. Includes Bly's "Jungian" interpretations of Grimm's fairy tales and readings of his own poetry.
World War II correspondence and memorabilia.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: University Librarian, University of California, Davis (1951-1974).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, memos, meeting minutes, annual reports, committee reports, publications.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Surgery, University of California, Davis. Blaisdell is considered the father of trauma care due to his development of a renowned trauma care system that was implemented at the Veterans Administration Hospital, San Francisco General Hospital and UC Davis. The Medical Library at the University of California, Davis is named in his honor.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Publications by Blaisdell on trauma care and surgery, research grants, and materials relating to the University of California, Davis School of Medicine and Medical Center.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Founded in 1956 by Edmund Simpson, M.D., of Placerville, California.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Pamphlets and botanical prints used as examples of work commissioned to the Blackwood Press.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Manufacturing firm located in Rio Vista, California since 1902 whose work focused on the development of tomato harvesters and other agricultural equipment.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Business records, correspondence, photographs, patent information, manuals, bills of material, drawings, blueprints, and specifications.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_moreinfo_name: View digitized films from the Blackwelder Manufacturing Records on the Internet Archive

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Karl Bissinger (1914- ), photojournalist and activist, was a friend of Julian Beck and Judith Malina, co-founders of The Living Theatre. Bissinger served as an occassional photographer of the Theatre and its performances.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, ephemera, photographs, posters, and programs pertaining to Living Theatre productions.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Viticulture, University of California, Berkeley (1904-1908, 1910-1935)
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, research material, publications by Bioletti, an extensive set of publications by others on a variety of agricultural topics, and a small series of specimen photographs.
Series of small books published by the Whitman Publishing Company. The books consist of stories based on comic strips, radio dramas, and popular fiction.
Material about the Old Campus Landfill/University of California, Davis.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Director of the United Nations Relief and Welfare Agency (1953-1955); Director of Field Operations for UNESCO (1955-1957); Director of the Sacramento Regional United Way.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, daybooks and journals, photographs, materials concerning Bialuski's scholastic work in Canada and his involvement with the United Nations Relief and Welfare Agency.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Business and acting manager to Mrs. Patrick Campbell, Marie Tempest, John Hare, Comyns Carr, and Henry Irving, among others.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, legal documents, photographs, programs, scripts, and Bertram's working papers and ephemera as theatrical agent and business manager for theatres, touring companies, and individual actors.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: French actress generally considered one of the most famous actresses of the early 20th century.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Clippings, engravings, caricatures, drawings, playbills, posters, programs, and more than three hundred pictures and photographs showing Bernhardt in her various roles.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Sociology, University of California, Davis (1963-1973); Professor of Sociology, University of California, San Diego (1973-1991).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, manuscripts of his writings, and subject files dealing with his research on counterculture and communes.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Viticulture and Enology, University of California, Davis; co-author of <cite>The technology of wine making</cite> (1962).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, photographs, department minutes, lab manuals, newsletters, bulletins, articles.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Chief Scientific Illustrator for the Bureau of Entomology, USDA; Senior Scientific Illustrator at the University of California, Davis.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Ten botanical lithographs. For examples of Benson's entomological illustrations, see the Howard Lester McKenzie Collection (D-309).

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: English character actor who played a variety of minor roles in Henry Irving's Lyceum Theatre.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, ephemera, photographs, playbills, programs, realia, and scripts. The bulk of this collection pertains to Henry Irving and his Lyceum Theatre company and includes original scripts and lighting plots used at the Lyceum Theatre.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: American stage manager, producer, and playwright known for his realistic stage sets.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Thirty-three photographs depicting Belasco's production of <cite>The Darling of the Gods</cite>, which opened December 3, 1902, at the Belasco Theatre in New York City.
Supply catalogs and other publications offering for sale a manufacturer's or retailer's apicultural line; some ephemeral material.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: President, M.L. Bayard and Co. (1941-1960). Internationally recognized wine connoisseur; founder of the Commanderie de Bordeaux sous Philadelphie.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: American and European wine catalogs and French price lists, especially those from the Bordeaux region.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Founded by Robert Woodruff in 1976, the Bay Area Playwrights Festival is an annual event focusing on writing and workshops led by eminent playwrights.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Playwright files, promotional materials, audio tapes, and video recordings.

title.rendered: Bartley, Basil G. D. Papers on Cacao.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Basil George David Bartley (1927-2008) spent a lifetime studying cacao.  Dr. Bartley was born in New Delhi, India and received his Ph.D. in Biology and Plant Breeding from Iowa State University (1950).  He is the author of <cite>The Genetic Diversity of Cacao and Its Utilization</cite> (CABI Publishing, 2005).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Field notebooks of observations on cacao and experiments in Brazil, Trinidad, and other countries; diaries containing field observations and summaries; books, pamphlets and extracts from literature on cacao; correspondence relating to cacao germplasm; and photographs, slides and recorded tape commentaries to accompany the field research notebooks.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Author of <cite>Laughing in the Hills</cite> (1980), <cite>Traveling Light</cite> (1984), <cite>Hard to Be Good</cite> (1987), <cite>Big Dreams: Into the Heart of California</cite> (1994), and <cite>Carson Valley</cite> (1997).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Barich's writing journals, manuscripts and published versions of his writings, promotional materials about his works, as well as literary and editorial correspondence.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Virology, University of California, Davis (1950-1978).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Research notes, laboratory and pathology data, reports, reprints, awards, correspondence, and slides related to Bankowski's work in infectious disease in poultry and swine.
Speeches by Phillip Bancroft and printed material about him and his candidacy for United States Senator.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Character actor and director and an original member of the Provincetown Players, an experimental group of actors and playwrights founded in 1916 by Susan Glaspell, George Cram Cook, Ida Rank, and Eugene O'Neill.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Clippings, playbills, programs, and photographs relating Ballantine's involvement with the Provincetown Players and other instances of his acting and directing career.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Bakken worked for over thirty years in agricultural advertising, primarily for Oliver Corporation, Minneapolis-Moline, and other companies associated with White Farm Equipment Division, White Motor Corporation.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Catalogs, dealer-only publications, advertising scripts, memoranda, speeches, reports, and photographs relating to agricultural technology, centering on the Oliver Corporation and its antecedents.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Art, University of California, Davis (1953-1985). Curator and art consultant to the California Historical Society (1962-1963; 1967-1970), owner of the North Point Gallery in San Francisco.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Research files covering 19th and 20th century painting, drawing, graphic art, sculpture, and architecture in California and Mexico, including exhibition catalogs, photographs, clippings, and research indexes of Californian artists; flyers and exhibition catalogs from public and private museums and art galleries around the world, including material describing the holdings of these places as well as of foundations and private collections.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Agricultural Engineering, University of California, Davis (1935-1969).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Curricula development, organizational conference agendas, and minutes for the College of Agriculture; manuscript (untitled) for a textbook on farm machinery (by Bainer, Kepner, Barger); miscellaneous journals and reports.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor, researcher, author and consultant in sustainable management.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Manuscripts and published versions of his writings which primarily focus on sustainability, solar energy, agroforestry, and restoration ecology.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Entomology, University of California, Davis (1930-1968).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence to researchers and growers regarding the control of croppests, as well as manuscripts of some of his writings, including severalon thrips.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Agent for California Grape Products Co., Ltd. (1922); Vice President and General Manager of Italian Vineyard Co. of Guasti, owned by CalGrape (1943); Vice President of CalGrape Products (1945); President of the Wine Institute (1948-50).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Papers, wine pamphlets, periodicals, books, clippings, and labels for grape products.
Several manuscript poems, including The Grove, Evening Thought, The Loss of Friends, and Hope.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Theatre collector from the Los Angeles, California area.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Clippings, programs, and scripts (sides and monologues) pertaining to California and Salt Lake City, Utah theatres in the early 1920's.
Graphic announcements of Avant-Garde poetry events.
Advertisements for book fairs, poetry readings, and other public events; press releases announcing new books and printing services.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Extensive collection of sheet music for piano, with an emphasis on sentimental music from the turn of the century; some research and classroom materials in mathematics theory and philosophy.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Michael Andrews (1944- ) is a poet, book artist, and photographer whose works include: <cite>Machu Picchu</cite>, <cite>The Place Where I Will Die</cite>, and <cite>RiverRun</cite>.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: The collection contains his works including manuscript and published editions as well as digital prints and mounted prints of his photography. Many of the images are taken in Southern California, specifically Hermosa Beach.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Chemistry, University of California, Davis (1953-1968).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Reprints of articles on organic chemistry.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Northern California poet and novelist; author of <cite>The doorway</cite> (1990); <cite>The woman who was wild</cite> (1989), and <cite>The rising of the flesh</cite> (1983).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence, poetry, journals, publications, and flyers.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Creator and director of the Richard L. Nelson Gallery and The Fine Arts Collection at the University of California, Davis; art lecturer and an artist.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Professor of Viticulture and Enology, University of California, Davis; author, lecturer, bibliographer, and consultant on wine matters.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Records, including correspondence, financial records, printed materials, membership cards.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Scripts, promotional materials, photographs, and reel-to-reel recordings relating to the production.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence and printed materials, as well as photograph and slidesrelating to cotton farming and legislation.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Collection represents the first major step in instituting an automated system capable of monitoring crop conditions and estimating crop production on a worldwide basis. Accompanying documents assist in the identification of small grains, such as wheat, using satellite imagery. This joint agricultural monitoring effort included the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, the U.S. Department of Agriculture, and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Aerial photographic negatives and transparencies of croplands. Country areas include Argentina, Australia, Brazil, Canada, China, India, USSR, and United States.
Manuals created by manufacturers to assist in the operation, maintenance, repair, or restoration of agricultural machinery.
Promotional and descriptive published materials relating to agricultural technology.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Legislative and Municipal Reference Librarian at the California State Library in the early 20th century.
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Correspondence from the files of J.L. Gillis to and from other universities regarding agricultural education appropriations.

acf.ucdlib_manuscript_biog: Bureau Chief, McClatchy Newspapers, San Francisco (1928-1935); organized and led the Wine Institute (1938-1954) and the Wine Advancement Board (1938-1954); author of <cite>The commonsense book of wine</cite> (1958), <cite>The commonsense book of drinking</cite> (1960), and <cite>The wines of America</cite> (1973).
acf.ucdlib_manuscript_descrip: Reports and brochures from the Wine Advisory Board and Wine Institute, files for <cite>The wines of America</cite>, correspondence and clippings, wine cookbooks and ephemera.
